abstract: Bernie Sanders has spent much of his career on the political margins, an outsider looking in.
snippet: Bernie Sanders has spent much of his career on the political margins, an outsider looking in.
lead_paragraph: CHARLESTON, S.C. — Bernie Sanders has spent much of his career on the political margins, an outsider looking in.
headline_main: Analysis: Sanders Learns What It's Like to Be a Front-Runner
headline_print_headline: Analysis: Sanders Learns What It's Like to Be a Front-Runner

abstract: With 17 contests at stake over the next week, the night took on a frenetic pace. Sanders faced the most scrutiny yet, Warren continued to bite into her rivals and Buttigieg and Klobuchar faded.
snippet: With 17 contests at stake over the next week, the night took on a frenetic pace. Sanders faced the most scrutiny yet, Warren continued to bite into her rivals and Buttigieg and Klobuchar faded.
lead_paragraph: From the opening bell, the Democratic candidates sparred with the desperation of the looming deadline. Sixteen states and territories will vote in the next week and everyone has little time to slow the building momentum of Senator Bernie Sanders, who leads in the early delegate chase and has won the most votes in each of the first three states.

abstract: The democratic socialist found himself in the center — of the stage and the squabbling.
snippet: The democratic socialist found himself in the center — of the stage and the squabbling.
lead_paragraph: Bernie Sanders was pointing — to the left, to the right, at himself, at the sky — in one moment coming under such ubiquitous duress that he extended both hands outward, as if pushing to the front of a crowd, to swat back stage-wide accusations of fuzzy math.

abstract: Democrats held their final debate before the South Carolina presidential primary and the critical Super Tuesday contests that follow three days later.
snippet: Democrats held their final debate before the South Carolina presidential primary and the critical Super Tuesday contests that follow three days later.
lead_paragraph: CHARLESTON, S.C. — Democrats held their final debate before the South Carolina presidential primary and the critical Super Tuesday contests that follow three days later.
headline_main: Debate Takeaways: Bernie Bruised but Not Broken

abstract: Campaign veterans reacted to how the Democratic presidential candidates fared Tuesday night.
snippet: Campaign veterans reacted to how the Democratic presidential candidates fared Tuesday night.
lead_paragraph: Twitter can’t tell us whether, or how, Tuesday’s debate might change voters’ minds. But it can give us the perspectives of some of the people with expertise on primary races: veteran campaign strategists, consultants and analysts. Here’s a rundown, with the candidates listed in alphabetical order.

abstract: In a messy Democratic forum, Bernie Sanders, the emerging front-runner, faced his most serious test so far. Michael R. Bloomberg also drew withering criticism.
snippet: In a messy Democratic forum, Bernie Sanders, the emerging front-runner, faced his most serious test so far. Michael R. Bloomberg also drew withering criticism.
lead_paragraph: CHARLESTON, S.C. — The Democratic presidential candidates delivered a barrage of criticism against their party’s emerging front-runner, Senator Bernie Sanders, at a debate on Tuesday night, casting him as a divisive figure with unrealistic ideas, even as they continued to batter Michael R. Bloomberg for his extreme wealth, his record on policing and his alleged behavior toward women.

snippet: Ms. Warren called out Mr. Bloomberg on his history of crude and sexist comments at the Democratic debate in Charleston, S.C.
lead_paragraph: In a moment that briefly froze the debate stage in Charleston, S.C., on Tuesday, Senator Elizabeth Warren explained why she thought Michael R. Bloomberg was the “riskiest” candidate for the Democratic Party to nominate, with a pointed recitation of his history of crude and sexist comments.
